bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Goddard Lieberson was born on April 5, 1911 in Hanley, Staffordshire, England. The family moved to Canada and then the United States in 1915, settling in Seattle, Washington. Lieberson attended North Queen Anne School between 1921 and 1925, and later, Ballard High School in Seattle. George McKay, a composition professor at the University of Washington arranged a scholarship that allowed Lieberson to attend the University as an undergraduate beginning in 1929. He studied at the University of Washington until 1932, after which he moved to pursue composition with Bernard Rogers at the Eastman School of Music in Rochester, New York.

Lieberson lived and worked in Rochester, New York until 1936. During his time there, he was as a music critic for local publications and a music teacher at Harley Day School. By 1939, Lieberson had moved to New York City, where he became quickly enmeshed in the musical community. He joined the Musicians Union and the Society of Professional Musicians, helped found the American Composers' Alliance, and became a critic for the popular publication Modern Music. After befriending John Hammond, who was then a record programmer in the Popular Music Division at Columbia Records, Lieberson was hired by Columbia as an assistant to Moses Smith, Director of Masterworks.
Lieberson rose through the ranks at Columbia, as documented in this Columbia Records biographical sketch, printed in July 1964:

"In 1939, [Lieberson] joined the Masterworks Division of Columbia Records, then newly acquired by the Columbia Broadcasting System, as Assistant Director. Subsequently, first as Director of that department and later as Vice President in charge of Masterworks Artists and Repertoire, he developed Columbia's distinguished classical artist roster and catalog. In 1949, Mr. Lieberson was appointed Executive Vice President of Columbia Records and, in 1956, he became President. At the same time, Mr. Lieberson became a Vice President and a member of the Board of Directors of the Columbia Broadcasting System, Inc. …"

Lieberson was instrumental in Columbia's rise to prominence in the recording industry. He had his hand in nearly every part of the recording process: programming, producing, editing and compiling marketing materials. Lieberson furthered the careers of numerous artists including Igor Stravinsky, Leonard Bernstein, Aaron Copland, Bruno Walter, Eugene Ormandy, Barbra Streisand, and many others. Alongside the development of the Long-Playing ("LP") record by Columbia in 1948, Lieberson spearheaded a number of important projects including Columbia's Modern American Music Series (1953). He was also instrumental to the production of over fifty original cast recordings of Broadway shows including My Fair Lady, The Sound of Music, and West Side Story. Lieberson produced a number of dramatic projects such as Waiting for Godot, Othello, and Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf, as well as historical documentaries including The American Revolution, The Confederacy, The Union, I Can Hear It Now, and numerous others.

By the time of his retirement in 1975, Lieberson had become a modern-day impresario in the record business. During the later years of his career he was less involved in day-to-day matters of production, but nevertheless participated in a number of important public projects that contributed to his legacy in the industry. He helped to found and curate the Yale University Collection of the Literature of the American Musical Theatre, sat on the advisory committee of the Hopkins Center at Dartmouth College, and served as president and member of the Board of Directors of the Record Industry Association of America (RIAA).

Lieberson was married for a brief time in the late 1930s to Margaret Rosenberg, whom he met in Rochester during his time at Eastman. They separated shortly after his move to New York. In 1946, Lieberson married actress and dancer Vera Zorina (known off-stage as Brigitta Lieberson), and they remained together until his death on May 29, 1977. They had two sons, Peter Lieberson (1946-2011), a notable composer, and Jonathan Lieberson (1949-1989), an editor and teacher of philosophy.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Goddard Lieberson Papers highlight Lieberson's career at Columbia Records and his work in the record business more broadly. His work as a producer, vice president, and president of the label is documented by an impressive volume of correspondence, published writings, business files, recording projects, and a selection of audio recordings and interviews. Particularly notable is the variety of correspondence between Lieberson and Columbia's recording artists, whose work spanned classical and popular music, musical theater productions, and historical documentary projects. Collaborators whose correspondence are in the collection include: Leonard Bernstein, Eugene Ormandy, Aaron Copland, Dave Brubeck, the New York Philharmonic, Igor Stravinsky, Lehman Engel, Samuel Beckett, Noël Coward, Truman Capote, Stephen Sondheim, Cole Porter, Richard Rodgers, Mary Martin, Rex Harrison, Barbra Streisand, Groucho Marx and dozens of others, as well. Also notable is the array of publicity materials and news clippings collected from contemporary publications that feature stories or press releases about Lieberson's projects or his personal success in the industry.

While there is a wealth of correspondence between Lieberson and collaborators, it is not always the case that full projects are documented in correspondence. Also note that the business documents give a general idea of Columbia's business proceedings, but do not provide an exhaustive account of Columbia's budgeting, marketing, or production procedures.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The papers are arranged in nine series. I. Correspondence, 1939-1977. II. Photographs, 1920-1975. III. Business Files, 1948-1978. IV. Audio, video and film, 1943-1977. V. Music and art, 1930-1960. VI. Writings by Goddard Lieberson, 1930-1975. VII. Writings by others, 1930-2000. VIII. Scrapbooks and programs, 1950-1975. VIIII. Personal documents and awards, 1957-1977.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Correspondence represents Goddard Lieberson's day-to-day activities as a record producer during his time at Columbia (c. 1939-1975). The series is organized into three subseries: Lettered Correspondence, Correspondence by Subject, and Correspondence by Date. The primary reason for these divisions is the organization of the material upon donation.

The Lettered Correspondence contains letters and memos exchanged between Lieberson and collaborators, colleagues, and artists. This subseries showcases Lieberson's collaborative and collegial relationships with Columbia recording artists, such as Igor Stravinsky, Arnold Schoenberg, Leonard Bernstein, Aaron Copland, Eugene Ormandy, David Diamond, Lehman Engel, Bruno Walter, and Artur Rodzinski.
Note that names and subjects also appear in the Business Files.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The letters are organized alphabetically, according to either individuals' names or names of organizations.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Correspondence by Date subseries is made up of a smaller group of dated correspondence from Lieberson's last years at the firm, until his death (c. 1974-1977).

This group of correspondence is very similar to the material in the previous two subseries. However, this group of letters was found together in a binder, and the decision was made to keep this arrangement.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Photographs Series includes black-and-white and color photographs. Subjects range from posed portraits of Goddard Lieberson to casual snapshots of family vacations. The "photo albums" subseries contains candid, professional-quality photographs depict Lieberson with various musicians and composers, often in the studio. These include artists such as Leonard Bernstein, Johnny Cash, Miles Davis, John Geilgud, Rex Harrison, Ethel Merman, Cole Porter, Igor Stravinsky and Teddy Wilson.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Each folder contains 10 photographs. The photographs are not in chronological order.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains a variety of materials related to Columbia Records and Columbia Foundation, Inc. (CFI). Sources include meeting notes for CFI, Lieberson's travel itineraries, and correspondence documenting Columbia's relationships with arts organizations across the country. With the exception of a few recording projects from the late 1940s, the material in this series dates from Lieberson's last decade as president of Columbia Records.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The files are arranged alphabetically within each subseries, except for the travel documents, which are organized by date.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains materials relating to select projects Lieberson either oversaw or participated in, between 1948 and 1978. Documents include correspondence, research sources, and other materials pertaining to Columbia's production and release of particular recordings. Included are recording projects from the "Legacy" series: "I Can Hear it Now" (1948), "The Union" and "The Confederacy" (1956), as well as recordings of Lieberson's String Quartet and Piano Pieces. The files here do not necessarily contain all available documentation of these projects, in which case the researcher is advised to consult related personal correspondence files, as well.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically according to project title.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: These files contain materials relating to Lieberson's last decade at the firm (c. 1965-1975), when he served as a member of the Board of the Columbia Foundation, Inc. (CFI). The documents range from board meeting notes (compiled in large folders, organized by meeting date) to correspondence and inter-Columbia business memos dealing with matters relating to the board or to the larger corporation. In general, these business materials differ from other Columbia business files in that they involve memberships and donations relating to CFI, not to Columbia Masterworks or Columbia Records. For correspondence and materials relating to recording projects, the researcher should consult the Columbia Projects sub-series or the correspondence series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains drafts and published copies of articles, essays, and creative projects by Goddard Lieberson over the course of his career. Topics include the recording industry, Lieberson's work at Columbia, and op-ed style critiques of music and art for publications such as The Saturday Review and Modern Music. Creative projects include Lieberson's novel, Three for Bedroom "C" (1947). Note that published reviews of Lieberson's writings (as well as his recording projects) can be found in the "Writings by Others" series.

Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains both writings by others about Lieberson and writings by others that Lieberson held in his possession. The writings about Lieberson include an array of published reviews, profile pieces, and news articles relating to Columbia. The bulk of these writings dates from 1930-1977. This series is a valuable resource for tracing the public reception of Columbia recording projects, as well as Lieberson's own cultural legacy. Among the writings by others that Lieberson held in his possession are several published works and manuscripts of writings by friends or acquaintances of Lieberson's including a typescript version of Aldous Huxley's Brave New World, and the Complete Catalog of Works by Carlos Chávez.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The first of two volumes celebrating Goddard Lieberson's twenty-five year anniversary at Columbia Records. Hardcover with reproduction of Al Hirschfeld's portrait of Lieberson on front cover. Inside pages contain upwards of 65 personalized notes of congratulations sent to Lieberson from famous artists and musicians with whom he worked during his first 25 years at the company. The first page of the volume includes a letter from William S. Paley, chairman of the board of directors at Columbia (and former president). Some photos of Lieberson are interspersed throughout the volume. Among the dozens of contributors to this volume, names include: Igor Stravinsky, Jacqueline Kennedy, Cole Porter, Richard Rodgers, Harold Prince, Truman Capote, and Rex Harrison. In addition to the letters contained in the volumes, the Goddard Lieberson Papers contain a small group of letters concerning the organization for these volumes and the twenty-fifth year anniversary, more generally.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The second of two volumes celebrating Goddard Lieberson's twenty-five year anniversary at Columbia Records. Hardcover with reproduction of Al Hirschfeld's portrait of Lieberson on front cover. Inside pages contain upwards of 65 personalized notes of congratulations sent to Lieberson from famous artists and musicians with whom he worked during his first 25 years at the company. Some photos of Lieberson are interspersed throughout the volume. Among the dozens that contributed to this volume, names include: Eugene Ormandy, Andre Kostelanetz, Gertrude Hindemith (on behalf of Paul Hindemith after his death), Aaron Copland, André Previn, and one letter signed by all members of The New York Philharmonic. In addition to the letters contained in the volumes, the Goddard Lieberson Papers contain a small group of letters concerning the organization for these volumes and the twenty-fifth year anniversary, more generally.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Of unknown origin. Contains newspaper and magazine clippings, photos, headlines, and various advertisements. Contains a number of pictures of Lieberson, cut from new articles or profiles. This is not a scrapbook in the sense of a photo album, or something put together to commemorate an event. Rather, it is an assemblage of cut-outs pasted together with no particular narrative or goal. Given the range of jokes and innuendos that cover the pages, this scrapbook seems to have been put together in jest, though there is no signature, date, or epigraph to provide context.
